{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6345e609-653e-42e5-8715-ffd846432fa5","content":"## What happened\n\nStarting in .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS**. Apple's Security framework (`Security.framework`) has never natively supported DSA, and .NET previously shipped a managed/OpenSSL-based shim to fill the gap. .NET 11 removed that shim, aligning with the broader deprecation of DSA (the `[Obsolete]` attributes added in earlier releases).\n\nOn Linux and Windows, `DSA.Create()` still works (OpenSSL and CNG support DSA), so only macOS breaks.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have a few options, depending on your constraints:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only)\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures, use [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography), which has a pure-managed DSA implementation that works everywhere:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, publicKeyParam);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n### Option 2 — Guard with a runtime check\n\nIf you want to keep using the built-in API on platforms that support it and fall back on macOS:\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // verify with built-in API\n}\nelse\n{\n    // BouncyCastle or OpenSSL interop fallback\n}\n```\n\n### Option 3 — Migrate signatures to a modern algorithm\n\nIf feasible, re-sign your artifacts with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, which are fully supported on all platforms. This eliminates the legacy DSA dependency entirely.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Apple never supported DSA natively; .NET 11 dropped the cross-platform shim. Use BouncyCastle for portable DSA signature verification, or migrate to ECDSA/RSA.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0d1aacc6-9051-452c-a69a-542469c4d054","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing older cryptographic algorithm support, particularly algorithms that Apple's Security framework no longer supports natively.\n\nSpecifically, DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) support on macOS has been affected by Apple dropping support for DSA in their cryptographic frameworks. In .NET, the `DSA.Create()` method on macOS would throw a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because the underlying Apple Security framework (CommonCrypto/Security.framework) no longer supports DSA.\n\n\nThe issue stems from .NET's reliance on Apple's Security framework for cryptographic operations on macOS. When Apple removed DSA support from their crypto libraries, .NET on macOS lost the ability to create DSA keys, resulting in the `PlatformNotSupportedException` when calling `DSA.Create()`. This appears to be the breaking change the user encountered between .NET 10 and .NET 11.\n\nFor workarounds, if the goal is just verifying existing signatures rather than generating new ones, there might be alternative approaches available. So the breaking change is likely that `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET 11, since the platform's native crypto library doesn't support DSA and .NET removed its managed fallback. I should focus on explaining what happened and providing clear migration strategies to help them move away from DSA.","outputTokens":1435,"requestId":"282F:527BE:1653684:18F7DAC:6A02858C"},"id":"69c98e88-a799-4b9c-8a17-3105fbd5abec","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:43:08.950Z","parentId":"6c1c2d51-1af9-45a6-a7ef-44ac00b5ef79"}
